  "prompt": "How does a half moon happen?",
  "response": "A half moon occurs as part of the moon's phases, which are caused by the relative positions of the moon, Earth, and the sun. The moon orbits around Earth, and depending on its position, the visible part of the moon changes. \n\nA half moon specifically refers to either the first quarter or third quarter moon:\n\n1. **First Quarter Moon**: This happens when the moon is located 90 degrees east of the sun in the sky. This phase occurs approximately one week after the new moon. The right half of the moon is illuminated and visible from Earth.\n\n2. **Third (or Last) Quarter Moon**: This occurs when the moon is positioned 90 degrees west of the sun. This phase takes place roughly three weeks after the new moon. The left half of the moon is illuminated and visible from Earth.\n\nDuring both phases, exactly half of the moon's visible surface is lit up by the sun, creating the appearance of a half moon from our perspective on Earth.",
